| Notes                   = * The world premiere was held at the {{WP|El Capitan Theatre}} on April 11, 2012.
* At the time of its release, the film broke numerous box office records, including the biggest opening weekend in North America and tied with ''{{WP|Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar}}'' and ''{{WP|Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows - Part 2}}'' for fastest film to gross $1 billion.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/13/the-avengers-1-billion-box-office_n_1513011.html|title=‘The Avengers’: $1 Billion In Global Box Office After Record Second Weekend|work=HuffPost|first=Christopher|last=Rosen|date=13 May 2012|accessdate=3 April 2018}} With a worldwide total box office gross of about $1.51 billion, this film became the highest grossing film of 2012, and at its peak the fifth highest-grossing film of all time.{{cite|ref=true|url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2012&p=.htm|title= 2012 Yearly Box Office Results|work= Box Office Mojo|accessdate= April 3, 2018}}{{cite|ref=true|url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/|title= All Time Worldwide Box Office Grosses|accessdate= April 3, 2018|work= Box Office Mojo|archiveurl= https://archive.is/yK8kb|archivedate= April 3, 2018}}
* ''Marvel's The Avengers'' is the first film in the [[Earth-199999|Marvel Cinematic Universe]] to be released by Walt Disney Pictures. Four of the preceding Marvel Studios productions (''[[Iron Man (film)|Iron Man]]'', ''[[Iron Man 2 (film)|Iron Man 2]]'', ''[[Thor (film)|Thor]]'' and ''[[Captain America: The First Avenger]]'') were released by Paramount Pictures and ''[[The Incredible Hulk (2008 film)|The Incredible Hulk]]'' was released by Universal Studios. The Paramount logo appears on Avengers posters and the film's opening titles as part of the deal between Disney and Paramount. Walt Disney Pictures is not credited until the final moments after the credits.
| Trivia                  = [[File:The Avengers (film) poster 011 (English version).jpg|thumb|right|125px|UK version of the poster]]
* Walt Disney Pictures retitled the film in the United Kingdom and Ireland to avoid confusion with {{WP|The Avengers (TV series)|the unrelated 1961 British TV series of the same title}}, which in turn had its own {{WP|The Avengers (1998 film)|similarly titled movie adaptation in 1998}}. The film was retitled ''Avengers Assemble'', after the popular catchphrase from the comic books. The reaction to the title change was mixed.
* The post-credits scene was filmed on the 12th of April<ref>[http://collider.com/the-avengers-filming-new-scene/158987/ Collider]</ref> (after ''Marvel's The Avengers'' world premiere). It features the six Avengers eating at the shawarma restaurant mentioned by Stark. {{WP|Chris Evans (actor)|Chris Evans}} had to wear a prosthetic face mask to hide his beard growth and further conceals the mask behind his hand as he eats. Due to the late filming of this scene, it was not ready for the international release on the 25th and therefore does not appear on ''Marvel's The Avengers'' presentations in many countries.
* The shawarma restaurant scene was inspired by [[Joss Whedon]]'s own work in the TV series ''{{WP|Angel (1999 TV series)|Angel}}'', namely the ending of the {{WP|Angel (season 5)|fifth season}}'s fifteenth episode.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/article/joss-whedons-favorite-angel-death-led-to-the-avengers-post-credits-scene|title=Joss Whedon's Favorite "Angel" Death Led to "The Avengers" Post-Credit Scene|work=Comic Book Resources|first=Jesse|last=Gormley|date=18 August 2016|accessdate=18 August 2016}}
* According to director Joss Whedon, {{WP|Scarlett Johansson}}'s participation in the film was in question early in the film's development. Because of this, Whedon's original script for the film included [[Wasp]] in her place.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.superherohype.com/news/articles/174139-joss-whedon-says-his-avengers-script-originally-included-the-wasp|title=Joss Whedon Says His Avengers Script Originally Included The Wasp|website=SuperHeroHype|last=Lesnick|first=Silas|date=18 December 2012|accessdate=2 January 2013|quote="There was a little bit of time where we thought we might not actually get Scarlett [Johansson]," he explains. "There was a very Waspy draft that I wrote. But it was way too Waspy. I was like, 'She's adorable! I'm just going to watch her!'"}}
* Disney and Sony Pictures agreed for [[Oscorp Tower]] from ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 film)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]'' to be included in the film, but the idea was dropped because much of the skyline had already been completed.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://latino-review.com/2012/06/spider-man-the-avengers-sort/|title=How Spider-Man was Almost in 'The Avengers,' Sort Of|author=Da7e|work=Latino Review|date=11 June 2012|accessdate=6 September 2013}}
* The scene where [[Bruce Banner (Earth-199999)|Bruce Banner]] describes how he tried to shoot himself but failed was seen in a deleted scene of ''The Incredible Hulk'', where Banner was in the Arctic. [[Steven Rogers (Earth-199999)|Captain America]] makes a cameo in this scene as well, where he and his shield are seen briefly as the ice shatters.
*While developing the film, worried that [[Loki Laufeyson (Earth-199999)|Loki Laufeyson]] wouldn't be enough match for the [[Avengers (Earth-199999)|Avengers]], Joss Whedon added [[Zeke Stane]] to the story as another enemy for the Avengers after his [[Obadiah Stane (Earth-199999)|father]]'s death, but [[Kevin Feige]] suggested Whedon to drop the idea.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/the-avengers-battle-of-new-york-joss-whedon|title=The Battle of New York: An 'Avengers' Oral History|last=PAtches and Failes|first=Matt and Ian|work=Thrillist|date=23 April 2018|accessdate=23 October 2020}}
* The [[Xu Wenwu (Earth-199999)|Mandarin]] and Shang-Chi were considered to appear in the post-credits scene as a tease for the Chinese market, but Beijing's development team shot down the idea as they didn't want the first Chinese character of the [[Earth-199999|Marvel Cinematic Universe]] to be a villain but there was no desire to cast any actor as Shang-Chi, leading Marvel to ultimately desist from the idea and instead filmed the tease with [[Thanos (Earth-199999)|Thanos]].{{cite|ref=true|url=https://bleedingcool.com/movies/marvel-studios-offered-shang-chi-or-mandarin-for-first-avengers-movie/|title=Marvel Studios Offered Shang-Chi Or Mandarin For First Avengers Movie|last=Johnston|first=Rich|work=Bleeding Cool|date=6 August 2020|accessdate=23 October 2020}}

